    "## Background\n",
    "\n",
    "Having stuck with the BV circuit for some time now, let us branch out to other uses of dynamic circuits.  There is a wide variety of examples that are impossible to implement without dynamic circuits.  One of the most cited examples is that of quantum teleportation, where entanglement between qubits and classical communication is used to move the state of one qubit to another.  Another prominent use case area for dynamic circuits is quantum error correction (QEC).  Here we will examine examples of both."
   ]

    "## Quantum teleportation\n",
    "\n",
    "Quantum teleportation is an example of utilizing quantum entanglement and classical resources to transfer quantum information from a sender to a receiver.  That we transfer the information, as oppose to copying it, is a requirement of the [No-cloning theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No-cloning_theorem), which forbids one from copy an unknown quantum state.\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we want to teleport the state for qubit C $|\\psi\\rangle_{\\rm C}= \\alpha|0\\rangle_{\\rm C} +\\beta|1\\rangle_{\\rm C}$ that is shared with qubit A (Alice) over to qubit B (Bob).  First we create a Bell pair (entanglement resource) between A and B, such that the state of the complete system is (in Qiskit bit-ordering):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "|\\Psi\\rangle_{\\rm BAC} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\left[ |00\\rangle_{\\rm BA} + |11\\rangle_{\\rm BA}\\right]\\otimes \\left[\\alpha|0\\rangle_{\\rm C}+\\beta |1\\rangle_{\\rm C}\\right]\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Now to proceed, we will make use of the Bell basis (In Qiskit bit-ordering):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "|B_{0}\\rangle = \\mathbb{I}\\otimes \\mathbb{I}|B_{0}\\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\left[|00\\rangle+|11\\rangle\\right] \\\\\n",
    "|B_{1}\\rangle = Z\\otimes \\mathbb{I}|B_{0}\\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\left[|00\\rangle-|11\\rangle\\right]\\\\\n",
    "|B_{2}\\rangle = X\\otimes \\mathbb{I}|B_{0}\\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\left[|01\\rangle+|10\\rangle\\right]\\\\\n",
    "|B_{3}\\rangle = ZX\\otimes \\mathbb{I}|B_{0}\\rangle = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\left[|01\\rangle-|10\\rangle\\right]\\\\\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, in circuit notation, each Bell state can be formed via:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "75b05b07",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-12-02T17:02:00.546587Z",
     "start_time": "2022-12-02T17:02:00.419263Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def bell_basis(index):\n",
    "\n",
    "    bell = QuantumCircuit(2)\n",
    "    bell.h(0)\n",
    "    bell.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "    if index == 0:\n",
    "        pass\n",
    "    elif index == 1:\n",
    "        bell.z(1)\n",
    "    elif index == 2:\n",
    "        bell.x(1)\n",
    "    elif index == 3:\n",
    "        bell.x(1)\n",
    "        bell.z(1)\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        raise ValueError('Index must be in [0,1,2,3]')\n",
    "    return bell"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "50cbbb88",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If we do a basis change and express the combined state of qubits A & C in terms of the Bell states, then the full tripartite system can be written as (ignoring overall factor of 1/2):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "|\\Psi\\rangle_{\\rm BAC} =& |\\psi\\rangle_{B}\\otimes|B_{0}\\rangle_{(AC)}+ \\\\\n",
    "&Z|\\psi\\rangle_{B}\\otimes|B_{1}\\rangle_{(AC)} + \\\\\n",
    "&X|\\psi\\rangle_{B}\\otimes |B_{2}\\rangle_{(AC)} + \\\\\n",
    "&ZX|\\psi\\rangle_{B}\\otimes |B_{3}\\rangle_{(AC)}\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "That is to say that, if we measure the state of AC to be in the i-th Bell state, then qubit B is in the desired state modulo the same gates needed to construct the i-th Bell state.  If we know, i.e. measure, AC to be in the i-th Bell state, then we know which gates we need to apply to fix this.  We therefore need to figure out how to measure Bell states.  It is important to note that **we have not done anything but express A and C in a different basis and rearrange terms**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c1099e51",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In order to pick out the particular Bell state via measurements, we need to perform a Bell measurement on pair AC.  The circuit for this is"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "b11e83e3",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-12-02T17:13:36.595760Z",
     "start_time": "2022-12-02T17:13:36.425766Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 580.387x284.278 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 250,
       "width": 490
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "bell_meas = QuantumCircuit(2)\n",
    "bell_meas.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "bell_meas.h(0)\n",
    "bell_meas.measure_all()\n",
    "bell_meas.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a6d521aa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In particular, it can be shown that a Bell measurement on the state $|B_{i}\\rangle$ yields the binary representation of the integer $i$, e.g. $i=2$ yields the bit-string `10`.  Whats more is that the resulting bit-string tells us which gate(s) we need to correct for. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "9bee33b5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim = AerSimulator()"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",

      "Bell measurement of B(1): {'01': 100}\n",
      "Bell measurement of B(2): {'10': 100}\n",
      "Bell measurement of B(3): {'11': 100}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for i in range(4):\n",
    "    print(\"Bell measurement of B({}):\".format(i),\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f4d1b61d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    " Here we make a circuit that generates a random initial state for qubit C, and teleports it to qubit B via the above method.  To verify that the state was generated, here we apply the inverse of the unitary used to generate the state, and look to see if we get back to the ground state."

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "d1229aba",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {

    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a random state for qubit C\n",
    "random_1q_gate = random_unitary(2).to_instruction()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "841d554b",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-12-02T18:57:28.370602Z",
     "start_time": "2022-12-02T18:57:27.979177Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1459.65x367.889 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 317,
       "width": 1202
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create a random state for qubit C\n",
    "random_1q_gate = random_unitary(2).to_instruction()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a register for each qubit of interest\n",
    "qrA = QuantumRegister(1, 'qA')\n",
    "qrB = QuantumRegister(1, 'qB')\n",
    "qrC = QuantumRegister(1, 'qC')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a single classical register\n",
    "cr = ClassicalRegister(2)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create circuit\n",
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(qrC, qrA, qrB, cr)\n",
    "# Make C qubit in random quantum state\n",
    "qc.compose(random_1q_gate, qrC, inplace=True)\n",
    "# Form Bell pair between A and B\n",
    "qc.h(qrA)\n",
    "qc.cx(qrA, qrB)\n",
    "qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Bell measurement\n",
    "qc.cx(qrC, qrA)\n",
    "qc.h(qrC)\n",
    "qc.measure([0,1], [0,1])\n",
    "\n",
    "qc.barrier()\n",
    "# Corrective Pauli gates\n",
    "# If returned bit-string is 01 = 1\n",
    "qc.z(qrB).c_if(cr, 1)\n",
    "# If returned bit-string is 10 = 2\n",
    "qc.x(qrB).c_if(cr, 2)\n",
    "# If returned bit-string is 11 = 3\n",
    "qc.z(qrB).c_if(cr, 3)\n",
    "qc.x(qrB).c_if(cr, 3)\n",
    "\n",
    "qc.barrier()\n",
    "# Apply inverse of unitary that generated state C\n",
    "qc.compose(random_1q_gate.inverse(), qrB, inplace=True)\n",
    "# Measure the Z component of B (overwriting the previous result)\n",
    "# We should be back in the ground state\n",
    "qc.measure(qrB, 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },

    "## Bit-flip code\n",
    "\n",
    "The bit-flip code is one of the simplest examples of a stabilizer code.  It is capable of protecting the encoded version of our state from single bit-flip (x-gate) errors. Here we will do a simple demonstration of this, correcting for a single-round of errors. \n",
    "\n",
    "Let the initial state be $|\\psi\\rangle = \\alpha|0\\rangle +\\beta|1\\rangle$.  The encoding needed for the bit-flip code mirrors this state onto the 3-qubit state\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "|\\psi\\rangle_{\\rm rep} = \\alpha|000\\rangle +\\beta|111\\rangle\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We cannot measure the qubits in the state directly, or we would destroy the state.  Therefore, we will need additional ancilla qubits on which to write the parity of the qubits.  Moreover, measuring individual qubits does not give enough knowledge to determine on which qubit an error occurred.  Rather, we need to measure the parity of *pairs* of qubits to determine which qubit has been flipped.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we will look at joint parity measurements of qubits $Q0\\oplus Q1$, as well as $Q1 \\oplus Q2$, stored as classical bits 0 and 1, respectively.  So see how this works, let us look at what the measurement yields for each possible case of a single bit-flip.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Error on Q0:\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     \\alpha|001\\rangle+\\beta|110\\rangle\\ \\ \\rightarrow \\ \\ 01\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     \n",
    "- Error on Q1:\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     \\alpha|010\\rangle+\\beta|101\\rangle\\ \\ \\rightarrow \\ \\ 11\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     \n",
    "- Error on Q2:\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     \\alpha|100\\rangle+\\beta|011\\rangle\\ \\ \\rightarrow \\ \\ 10\n",
    "     $$\n",
    "     \n",
    "We see that the joint parity measurement information allows us to identify which of the three qubits had a error.  We can then use this measurement information to conditionally flip the erroneous bit."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "34172f1e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we start with an arbitrary 1Q state, encode it into the bit-flip code and correct any single-flips that might have occurred.  To check the validity of the correction, we attempt to undo the encoding and arbitrary state, and measure how close we return to the ground state."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "1a4f4149",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Generate random 1Q gate\n",
    "random_1q_gate = random_unitary(2).to_instruction()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 534,
   "id": "6a6a28c6",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-12-02T20:05:48.092465Z",
     "start_time": "2022-12-02T20:05:47.605063Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1952.02x535.111 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 534,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 453,
       "width": 1601
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create a register for each qubit of interest\n",
    "qr1 = QuantumRegister(3, 'state')\n",
    "qr2 = QuantumRegister(2, 'ancilla')\n",
    "cr = ClassicalRegister(3, 'c')\n",
    "\n",
    "qc2 = QuantumCircuit(qr1, qr2, cr)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Encode state\n",
    "qc2.compose(random_1q_gate, [qr1[0]], inplace=True)\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[0], qr1[1])\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[0], qr1[2])\n",
    "\n",
    "qc2.barrier()\n",
    "# Joint party of 0 and 1 onto ancilla 0\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[0], qr2[0])\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[1], qr2[0])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Joint party of 1 and 2 onto ancilla 1\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[1], qr2[1])\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[2], qr2[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "qc2.barrier()\n",
    "# Perform the syndrome measurement\n",
    "qc2.measure(qr2[0], 0)\n",
    "qc2.measure(qr2[1], 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Conditionally flip bits\n",
    "# We need to use the old c_if syntax in order to do noisy simulations\n",
    "qc2.x(qr1[0]).c_if(cr,1)\n",
    "qc2.x(qr1[1]).c_if(cr,3)\n",
    "qc2.x(qr1[2]).c_if(cr,2)\n",
    "\n",
    "qc2.barrier()\n",
    "# Undo computation and measure if back in ground state\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[0], qr1[2])\n",
    "qc2.cx(qr1[0], qr1[1])\n",
    "qc2.compose(random_1q_gate.inverse(), [qr1[0]], inplace=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Record the probability of being back in the ground state\n",
    "qc2.measure(0, 2)\n",
    "qc2.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "84fde9d6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Simulation\n",
    "\n",
    "Because we are correcting noisy behavior, we will need a noisy simulator to inject bit-flip errors.  There is no Peekskill noisy simulator, and we currently cannot build one from the new provider backends, so we will use another system here:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 535,
   "id": "5b4cfe9d",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-12-02T20:15:46.929515Z",
     "start_time": "2022-12-02T20:15:46.918088Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim = FakeHanoi()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1fff7f1f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We have two different pieces of information in our counts.  First, the ancilla bits contain the information on what errors, and how many occurred.  The second bit records how often our system should be in the ground state.  Ideally this is 100% of the time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 536,
   "id": "bcb7e6a7",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-12-02T20:15:54.467451Z",
     "start_time": "2022-12-02T20:15:50.172448Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim_counts2 = sim.run(qc2, shots=10000).result().get_counts()\n",
    "anc_counts = marginal_counts(sim_counts2, [0,1])\n",
    "ans_counts = marginal_counts(sim_counts2, [2])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 542,
   "id": "2baebf94",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-12-02T20:24:33.566487Z",
     "start_time": "2022-12-02T20:24:33.562133Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Errors detected: {'01': 112, '10': 79, '00': 9767, '11': 42}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ef575315",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that errors occur a couple hundred of time, but the vast majority of time there are no qubit errors.  Taken together with the fact that we are correcting errors, the final qubit should be found in the ground state with high-probability."
   ]
  },
